about identity. And he was very
interested

45:08.973 --> 45:10.808 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
in that.

45:10.908 --> 45:12.810 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And then, of
course, it happens
to him. And he starts -- as he's
dying, he's

45:12.910 --> 45:19.050 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
thinking about, if you're dying,
rather than
living, in a sense, then are you
still you?

45:19.150 --> 45:23.955 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. LUCY KALANITHI: In the
moment of diagnoses,
he sort of saw his life
trajectory and his

45:24.055 --> 45:29.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
self kind of come tumbling down.
He wasn't
going to be a neurosurgeon for
years and years.

45:29.226 --> 45:33.664 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we thought initially that he
actually
had less time to live. We
thought he might

45:33.764 --> 45:38.336 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have months or less than a year.
And then
he started a therapy that
allowed him a lot

45:38.436 --> 45:42.840 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
more kind of functionality than
he expected
and a longer prognosis
potentially. And so

45:42.940 --> 45:47.178 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
then it was this big question
of, I don't
know how much time I have left
and how do

45:47.278 --> 45:48.946 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I spend that time? Who am I?

45:49.046 --> 45:51.882 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Paul spoke of
this in a video
released by his publisher.

45:51.983 --> 45:58.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL KALANITHI: It's a careful
load to balance.
If you don't think about the bad
case, that

45:58.155 --> 46:00.625 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ending is going to be very rough
on you and
your family.

46:00.725 --> 46:05.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But if you don't think about the
good case,
you're going to miss an
opportunity to really

46:05.296 --> 46:08.199 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
make the most out of your life
and time.

46:08.299 --> 46:14.372 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You know, one of
the things
that struck me also here is, he
learns a lot

46:14.472 --> 46:17.041 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about doctoring, right, that he
had never
seen as a doctor.

46:17.141 --> 46:19.010 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DR. LUCY KALANITHI: Yes, yes,
yes.

46:19.110 --> 46:22.046 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: He writes, for
example, at
one point, "Realizing how little
doctors understand

46:22.146 --> 46:24.015 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the hells through for which we
put patients."

46:24.115 --> 46:26.450 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He was really getting to see
things from a
different side.

46:26.550 --> 46:30.821 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. LUCY KALANITHI: He had been
in medicine
for a decade as a student and
then a resident,

46:30.921 --> 46:35.660 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
but all these tiny little
experiences -- like,
as an example, when you get an
I.V. and they

46:35.760 --> 46:39.864 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
start infusing normal saline
into your vein,
you can taste the salt.

46:39.964 --> 46:43.334 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he said: "I have been a
doctor for a decade,
and I never knew you could taste
the salt."

46:43.434 --> 46:48.205 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's all these tiny details
that sort
of come to the fore. And that's
not even to

46:48.305 --> 46:53.744 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
mention the physical and
emotional suffering
that comes with being sick and
the way it

46:53.844 --> 46:58.616 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
rocks you and rocks your family.
So, yes,
we really kind of felt that.

46:58.716 --> 47:04.388 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: He could look at
it intellectually,
but he also then had to look at
it very realistically.

47:04.488 --> 47:06.223 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DR. LUCY KALANITHI: Yes.

47:06.323 --> 47:10.194 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When we got the news of this
terrible chest
X-ray that looked really kind of
dense with

47:10.294 --> 47:14.432 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
tumors, and kind of helped
explain why he
had been having weight loss and
back pain

47:14.532 --> 47:20.104 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and real kind of health troubles
for a few
months, both of us knew that the
next day

47:20.204 --> 47:24.375 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we were going to the hospital.
He would have
a C.T. scan and it would likely
show metastatic

47:24.475 --> 47:26.210 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
cancer.

47:26.310 --> 47:30.548 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Being doctors, we could see that
path. And
when we packed for the hospital,
I was packing

47:30.648 --> 47:37.154 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
socks and pillows and phone
chargers, and
he just packed three books. He
packed "Mere

47:37.254 --> 47:44.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Christianity" by C.S. Lewis,
Heidegger's "Being
and Time," and Solzhenitsyn's
"Cancer Ward."

47:44.295 --> 47:48.699 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And I think it was that
transition right away
where he said: "This is becoming
so personal

47:48.799 --> 47:54.038 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that I need my books. Like, I
need to understand
this through literature."

47:54.138 --> 47:58.142 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When he became ill, he kind of
translated
the experience back into writing
and words

47:58.242 --> 48:01.045 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to make sense of it. And this
book is part
of that.

48:01.145 --> 48:02.747 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And what about
for you? What
did you feel when you read it?

48:02.847 --> 48:05.549 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DR. LUCY KALANITHI: So, I read
it in real
time, as he was writing it.

48:05.649 --> 48:10.221 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I would read it daily or weekly.
And it was
kind of a great communication
tool for us,

48:10.321 --> 48:10.921 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
actually.

48:11.021 --> 48:12.256 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Oh, really?

48:12.356 --> 48:14.158 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DR. LUCY KALANITHI: Because he
would talk
about -- oh, yes.

48:14.258 --> 48:16.127 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Seeing him write the book was
really amazing,
because even though his body was
sort of in

48:16.227 --> 48:24.301 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this state of physical collapse,
his mind
was so engaged, still, in this
process.

48:24.401 --> 48:29.240 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And kind of the reviews of the
book that I
like the best capture that
somewhat. There's

48:29.340 --> 48:32.743 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
an author named Gavin Francis
who wrote a
blurb for the book. And he wrote
something

48:32.843 --> 48:36.781 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
like, "This is a tremendous
book, crackling
with life."

48:36.881 --> 48:41.185 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that idea, like, it brings
tears to my
eyes to think of crackling with
life, because,

48:41.285 --> 48:44.655 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
if you had seen Paul, you know,
he's wrapped
up in a blanket, he's sitting in
this armchair.

48:44.755 --> 48:47.925 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He looks frail and wan, you
know? He looks
ill.

48:48.025 --> 48:49.827 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: As he's writing?

48:49.927 --> 48:54.231 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. LUCY KALANITHI: But he's
crackling with
life. And that was just really
true. And the

48:54.331 --> 48:56.267 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
book was a big part of that.

48:56.367 --> 49:01.939 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The two of you
made a very
important, major decision in the
midst of

49:02.039 --> 49:03.174 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
this, which was to have a child.

49:03.274 --> 49:04.842 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DR. LUCY KALANITHI: That's
right.

49:04.942 --> 49:07.077 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Was that a tough
decision?

49:07.178 --> 49:12.383 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. LUCY KALANITHI: We had
always wanted to
have children together. We
hadn't done it

49:12.483 --> 49:16.420 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by the end of his residency.
That was around
the time we had pictured we
always would.

49:16.520 --> 49:22.359 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And right at that time was when
he was diagnosed
with terminal cancer, terminal
lung cancer.

49:22.459 --> 49:27.431 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it was a series of really
intense conversations
to figure out if we wanted to do
that and

49:27.531 --> 49:31.635 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
could we handle that, and both
of us had the
instinct to do it.

49:31.735 --> 49:35.439 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we needed to think very hard
about what
it would mean. You know, we
talked really

49:35.539 --> 49:39.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
frankly about his prognosis and
what was happening.
And I said that, "Don't you
think that saying

49:39.777 --> 49:42.780 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
goodbye to a child would make
your death even
more painful?"

49:42.880 --> 49:45.649 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And he said, "Well, wouldn't it
be great if
it did?"

49:45.749 --> 49:52.489 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL KALANITHI: Since Cady's
birth, my time
with her has had a very peculiar
and free

49:52.590 --> 49:59.463 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
nature. In all probability, I
won't live long
enough for her to remember me,
and so the

49:59.563 --> 50:01.265 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
time is -- just is what it is.

50:01.365 --> 50:03.968 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. LUCY KALANITHI: That was
kind of this
amazing thing, where it's like
life isn't

50:04.068 --> 50:08.005 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
just about avoiding suffering.
It's about
finding meaning. And having a
child was part

50:08.105 --> 50:09.840 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of that for us.

50:09.940 --> 50:14.745 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The very powerful
book is "When
Breath Becomes Air" by Paul
Kalanithi.

50:14.845 --> 50:16.213 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Lucy Kalanithi, thank you so
much.

50:16.313 --> 50:27.191 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DR. LUCY KALANITHI: My pleasure.
