50:58.522 --> 51:01.959 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Here, she speaks about
fearlessness and black
art.

51:02.059 --> 51:04.094 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RACHEL KAADZI GHANSAH, Author,
"The Explainers
and the Explorers": I like
writing about people

51:04.194 --> 51:09.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who look like me and the people
I know who
don't have good pieces written
about them,

51:09.566 --> 51:12.770 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
because we deserve it.

51:12.870 --> 51:22.579 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I have written about Jimi
Hendrix, Electric
Lady Studios, Toni Morrison,
Kendrick Lamar,

51:22.680 --> 51:26.884 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Watts riots, Trayvon Martin,
Rachel Jeantel,
Dave Chappelle.

51:26.984 --> 51:31.989 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We don't always hear about the
people who
we know as legends the ways that
they were

51:32.089 --> 51:36.226 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
very true to themselves. I'm
more interested
in the moments when they were
uncompromising

51:36.327 --> 51:40.998 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and they were fearless, because
what I hope
is that that fearlessness tells
us a little

51:41.098 --> 51:42.967 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
bit about how we can be
fearless.

51:43.067 --> 51:47.371 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What was interesting to me about
Dave Chappelle
is, here is a moment where
typically walking

51:47.471 --> 51:52.810 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
away from Comedy Central,
walking away from
your career would be a bad
decision, and anyone

51:52.910 --> 51:58.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
would tell you, don't do that.
The common
understanding of it is, is that
he felt that

51:58.349 --> 52:02.886 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the show had started to cross a
line, and
that it was actually becoming a
source of

52:02.987 --> 52:08.892 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
embarrassment. And so walking
away from $50
million was pretty heroic and
pretty decent

52:08.993 --> 52:10.761 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and full of integrity.

52:10.861 --> 52:14.865 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, you know, I couldn't read
until I was
12. And maybe I wasn't 12, but I
was older.

52:14.965 --> 52:18.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think people start reading
when they're
5 or something. And so books
were kind of

52:18.335 --> 52:24.775 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this phantasmagorical space that
I couldn't
enter because my mom could read.
My dad was

52:24.875 --> 52:28.379 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
an academic. Everyone was so
intelligent.
And I couldn't go there.

52:28.479 --> 52:33.484 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the moment I could, I just
started to
read ravenously. One of the
books that I remember

52:33.584 --> 52:41.125 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
changing everyone's lives was
"Beloved." That
was the first time people who
had been silenced,

52:41.225 --> 52:43.627 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
enslaved people, became human.

52:43.727 --> 52:50.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, at that moment, I said,
this is what
a writer can do. And, so, for
me, Toni Morrison

52:50.267 --> 52:56.140 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
