She almost
exists in this odd, spiritual,
otherworld,

52:56.240 --> 53:02.813 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in terms of her work. And when
she won that
Nobel Prize, what was
interesting is that

53:02.913 --> 53:07.618 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a lot of prominent newspapers
asked, does
this woman deserve it?

53:07.718 --> 53:13.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, when I had the moment to
take the "New
York Times" magazine cover, I
decided I'm

53:13.157 --> 53:17.694 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
going to take that cover to lay
flowers at
the feet of this woman and say,
not only did

53:17.795 --> 53:20.230 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
you deserve it, but thank you.

53:20.330 --> 53:25.869 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
My name is Rachel Kaadzi
Ghansah, and this
is my Brief But Spectacular take
on fearlessness

53:25.969 --> 53:27.771 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and black art.

